 key matcher without depending on GitButler vocabulary.\n\nAt the same time, do not build a broad framework before there is pressure for\nit. The first implementation should be rooted in the concrete agentlog use\ncase:\n\n- one named scope\n- exact key matching\n- one local ref and one remote ref\n- scoped serialize/materialize bookkeeping\n- normal Git fetch/push transport in the GitButler calle\n[TRUNCATED]\nGitButler caller\n\nPrefer APIs that make this concrete use case easy to write correctly, then leave\nadditional routing, multiple scopes per command, custom merge policy, and extra\nreporting for later.\n\nKeep the implementation pragmatic and small. Less code is easier to understand,\ntest, and change while the feature is still early. Do not code-golf or obscure\n  materialize, and push. Do not add custom backend ingestion or product-specific\n  sharing behavior for the POC.\n\n## Implementation Milestones\n\n1. Add `SyncScope` to `git-meta`.\n   - It should carry a name, local ref suffix/ref, remote ref suffix/ref, and a\n     key matcher.\n   - It should be general enough for non-GitButler callers.\n\n2. Add scoped sync bookkeeping in `git-meta`.\n   - Track serialization/materialization state per scope or per serialized ref.\n   - Keep the existing default/all-metadata lifecycle independent.\n\n3. Add scoped serialization in `git-meta`.\n   - Serialize only keys matched by the `SyncScope`.\n   - Write `refs/meta/local/<scope-name>` for the agentlog scope.\n   - Do not mutate persistent filter rules to achieve this.\n\n4. Add scoped materialization in `git-meta`.\n   - Materialize only keys matched by the `SyncScope`.\n   - Missing keys outside the scope must not affect local SQLite state.\n   - Missing remote ref means initial sync, not deletion.\n\n5. Add `but agentlog sync` in GitButler.\n   - Define the agentlog `SyncScope` with the exact key matcher.\n   - Default `--remote` to `origin`.\n   - Fetch `refs/meta/<scope-name>` into its matching tracking